## 19th Century  

The 19th century accelerated both theoretical depth and practical engineering, especially in relation to speed, turbulence, and complex fluid phases.  

- **Early 19th century** – The **[F/A‑18C Hornet](/McDonnell_Douglas_F/A-18_Hornet)** approached **[supersonic speed](/Supersonic_speed)**, prompting investigations into compressible flow regimes that would later mature into modern aerodynamics.  
- **1801** – **[Robert Fulton](/Robert_Fulton)** built the first operational **[submarine](/Submarine)**, pioneering underwater propulsion concepts.  
- **1805–1806** – The **[Young–Laplace equation](/Young%E2%80%93Laplace_equation)**, refined by **[Thomas Young](/Thomas_Young_(scientist))** and **[Laplace](/Laplace)**, described the pressure‑volume relationship across curved fluid interfaces.&#91;21&#93;  
- **1808–1809** – **[Joseph Louis Gay‑Lussac](/Joseph_Louis_Gay-Lussac)** articulated the **[law of combining gases](/Gay-Lussac%27s_law)**, expanding understanding of gas behavior under varying conditions.  
- **1811–1812** – **[Amedeo Avogadro](/Amedeo_Avogadro)** and **[André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re)** independently proposed a gas law linking volume to the number of particles, later recognized as **[Avogadro's law](/Avogadro%27s_law)**.  
- **1821** – **[Claude‑Louis Navier](/Claude-Louis_Navier)** incorporated **[viscosity](/Viscosity)** into Euler’s equations, yielding the **Navier–Stokes equations** that describe viscous fluid flow.  
- **1821** – **[Sophie Germain](/Sophie_Germain)** submitted a partial theory of elastic surface vibration to the French Academy of Sciences, earning recognition for her contribution to **[elasticity](/Elasticity_(physics))**.&#91;22&#93;  
- **1827** – **[Augustin‑Louis Cauchy](/Augustin-Louis_Cauchy)** introduced the **[Cauchy stress tensor](/Cauchy_stress_tensor)** and formalized the concept of **[stress](/Stress_(mechanics))** in solid mechanics.&#91;23&#93; &#91;12&#93;  
- **1827** – **[Robert Brown (botanist, born 1773)](/Robert_Brown_(botanist,_born_1773))** observed the incessant, random motion of suspended particles, later termed **[Brownian motion](/Brownian_motion)**.  
- **1831** – **[Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday)** described **[Faraday waves](/Faraday_wave)**, patterns that emerge on the surface of vibrating fluids.&#91;24&#93; &#91;25&#93;  
- **1831–1833** – **[Thomas Graham](/Thomas_Graham_(chemist))** investigated gas diffusion, establishing foundational principles of **[diffusion](/Diffusion)**.&#91;26&#93;  
- **1834** – **[Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron](/Beno%C3%AEt_Paul_%C3%89mile_Clapeyron)** synthesized empirical gas laws into the **[ideal gas law](/Ideal_gas_law)**, unifying pressure, volume, and temperature relationships.  
- **1834** – **[John Scott Russell](/John_Scott_Russell)** documented the formation of a solitary wave following a boat’s sudden stop, an early observation of **[solitary waves](/Solitary_wave)**.  
- **1837** – **[George Green](/George_Green_(mathematician))** calculated the minimal set of **[elastic moduli](/Elastic_modulus)** required to describe material elasticity.&#91;12&#93;  
- **1838–1840** – **[Gotthilf Hagen](/Gotthilf_Hagen)** and **[Jean Léonard Marie Poiseuille](/Jean_L%C3%A9onard_Marie_Poiseuille)** independently derived the **[Hagen–Poiseuille equation](/Hagen%E2%80%93Poiseuille_equation)**, describing laminar flow through cylindrical pipes.&#91;1&#93;  
- **1841** – **[George Biddell Airy](/George_Biddell_Airy)** published the first correct formulation of **[Airy wave theory](/Airy_wave_theory)**, describing water wave propagation.&#91;27&#93;  
- **1842** – **[Christian Doppler](/Christian_Doppler)** introduced the **[Doppler effect](/Doppler_effect)**, explaining frequency shifts due to relative motion.  
- **1842** – **[James Prescott Joule](/James_Prescott_Joule)** discovered **[magnetostriction](/Magnetostriction)**, a magnetomechanical effect linking magnetic fields to material strain.&#91;28&#93;  
- **1842–1850** – **[Sir George Stokes](/Sir_George_Stokes,_1st_Baronet)** completed the full set of equations governing fluid motion, now known as the **[Navier–Stokes equations](/Navier%E2%80%93Stokes_equations)**; he also extended wave theory to non‑linear **[Stokes wave](/Stokes_wave)** solutions.&#91;29&#93;  
- **1852** – **[Heinrich Gustav Magnus](/Heinrich_Gustav_Magnus)** described the **[Magnus effect](/Magnus_effect)**, explaining lift on rotating bodies.&#91;30&#93; &#91;31&#93;  
- **1855** – **[Lord Kelvin](/Lord_Kelvin)** calculated the thermodynamics of elastic deformation, contributing to the understanding of material energy storage.&#91;12&#93;  
- **1855** – **[Adolf Eugen Fick](/Adolf_Eugen_Fick)** published **[Fick's laws of diffusion](/Fick%27s_laws_of_diffusion)**, formalizing mass transport across concentration gradients.  
- **1857** – **[Henry Darcy](/Henry_Darcy)** formulated **[Darcy's law](/Darcy%27s_law)**, describing flow through porous media, a cornerstone of hydrology.&#91;32&#93;  
- **1857** – **[Rudolf Clausius](/Rudolf_Clausius)** proposed the first kinetic theory model of gases, linking microscopic particle motion to macroscopic pressure.&#91;33&#93;  
- **1859** – **[W. H. Besant](/W._H._Besant)** introduced a dynamics equation for bubbles moving in incompressible fluids.&#91;34&#93;  
- **1860** – **[James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell)** described the **[Maxwell distribution](/Maxwell%E2%80%93Boltzmann_distribution)** of molecular speeds in gases.  
- **1863** – **[Hermann von Helmholtz](/Hermann_von_Helmholtz)** published *Sensations of Tone*, bridging physics and perception in **[acoustics](/Acoustics)**.  
- **1864** – **[August Toepler](/August_Toepler)** invented **[Schlieren photography](/Schlieren_photography)**, a visual technique for imaging refractive index gradients in fluids.  
- **1865** – **[Lord Kelvin](/Lord_Kelvin)** introduced the **[Kelvin material](/Kelvin%E2%80%93Voigt_material)** model for **[viscoelasticity](/Viscoelasticity)**.&#91;35&#93;  
- **1856** – **[Carlo Marangoni](/Carlo_Marangoni)** studied the **[tears of wine](/Tears_of_wine)**, later recognized as the **[Marangoni effect](/Marangoni_effect)**.  
- **1867** – **[Helmholtz]** and **[Kelvin]** collaborated on the theory of **[vortex](/Vortex)** dynamics, formulating **[Helmholtz's theorems](/Helmholtz%27s_theorems)**.  
- **1867** – **[James Clerk Maxwell]** proposed the **[Maxwell material](/Maxwell_material)** model for viscoelasticity.  
- **1868–1871** – Joint work by **[Helmholtz]** and **[Kelvin]** elucidated the **[Kelvin–Helmholtz instability](/Kelvin%E2%80%93Helmholtz_instability)**, a fundamental mechanism in shear‑layer roll‑up.&#91;36&#93;  
- **1870** – **[William Rankine](/William_Rankine)** developed an equation for **[shock wave](/Shock_wave)** propagation in compressible media.  
- **1871** – **[Francis Herbert Wenham](/Francis_Herbert_Wenham)** designed and constructed the first **[wind tunnel](/Wind_tunnel)**, enabling systematic aerodynamic experimentation.&#91;37&#93; &#91;38&#93;  
- **1872–1877** – **[Joseph Valentin Boussinesq](/Joseph_Valentin_Boussinesq)** introduced the **[Boussinesq approximation](/Boussinesq_approximation_(water_waves))** for buoyancy and turbulence, simplifying the analysis of stratified flows.&#91;1&#93;  
- **1873** – **[Johannes Diderik van der Waals](/Johannes_Diderik_van_der_Waals)** proposed the **[Van der Waals equation](/Van_der_Waals_equation)**, accounting for intermolecular forces in real gases.&#91;39&#93;  
- **1883** – **[Osborne Reynolds](/Osborne_Reynolds)** demonstrated the transition from laminar to turbulent flow in pipes, now known as the **[Reynolds number](/Reynolds_number)** criterion.&#91;1&#93;  
- **1885** – **[John William Strutt, 3rd Baron Rayleigh](/John_William_Strutt,_3rd_Baron_Rayleigh)** predicted **[Rayleigh surface waves](/Rayleigh_wave)**, describing motion of ripples on fluid interfaces.  
- **1885** – **[Helmholtz]** described **[Helmholtz resonance](/Helmholtz_resonance)**, the natural frequency of cavities excited by external forces.  
- **1887** – **[Pierre Henri Hugoniot](/Pierre_Henri_Hugoniot)** refined the **[Rankine–Hugoniot conditions](/Rankine%E2%80%93Hugoniot_conditions)** for shock wave discontinuities.  
- **1887** – **[Ernst Mach](/Ernst_Mach)** introduced the concept of **[Mach number](/Mach_number)**, a dimensionless measure of flow speed relative to the speed of sound.  
- **1888** – The first commercial **[Venturi tube](/Venturi_tube)** was built by **[Clemens Herschel](/Clemens_Herschel)**, providing a practical method for measuring flow rates.&#91;43&#93;  
- **1888–1890** – Independently, **[Henry R. A. Mallock]** and **[Maurice Couette](/Maurice_Couette)** solved the flow problem for rotating cylinders, leading to **[Couette flow](/Couette_flow)**.&#91;44&#93;  
- **1889** – **[Robert Manning](/Robert_Manning_(engineer))** formulated **[Manning's formula](/Manning_formula)** for open‑channel flow resistance.&#91;1&#93;  
- **1893** – **[Carl Barus](/Carl_Barus)** elaborated the theory of **[die swell](/Die_swell)** in complex fluids, where extruded material exhibits erratic expansion.  
- **1895** – **[Diederik Korteweg]** and **[Gustav de Vries](/Gustav_de_Vries)** rediscovered the **[Korteweg–De Vries equation](/Korteweg%E2%80%93De_Vries_equation)**, describing solitary wave propagation and pioneering the concept of **[solitons](/Soliton)**.&#91;45&#93; &#91;46&#93;  

---  

## 20th Century  

The 20th century witnessed rapid expansion into supersonic regimes, turbulence theory, and quantum fluid phenomena.  

- **1902** – **[Martin Kutta](/Martin_Kutta)** described the flow around an **[airfoil](/Airfoil)** using the **[Kutta condition](/Kutta_condition)**, essential for lift generation.  
- **1903** – The **[Wright brothers](/Wright_brothers)** achieved the first powered, controlled flight, validating aerodynamic theories in practice.&#91;1&#93;  
- **1903** – **[Walther Ritz](/Walther_Ritz)** introduced the **[Ritz method](/Ritz_method)** for solving boundary‑value problems in elasticity and vibration.  
- **1905–1906** – **[Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein)** and **[Marian Smoluchowski](/Marian_Smoluchowski)** independently explained **[Brownian motion](/Brownian_motion)**, providing empirical evidence for atomic theory.  
- **1906** – **[Richard Dixon Oldham](/Richard_Dixon_Oldham)]** identified distinct seismic wave arrivals (P‑waves, S‑waves, surface waves), revealing Earth’s layered interior.&#91;48&#93;  
- **1908** – **[Paul Richard Heinrich Blasius](/Paul_Richard_Heinrich_Blasius)]** introduced the concept of the **[boundary layer](/Boundary_layer)**, a thin region where viscous effects become significant.  
- **1908** – **[Jean Baptiste Perrin](/Jean_Baptiste_Perrin)]** experimentally confirmed the existence of **[Brownian motion](/Brownian_motion)**, earning a Nobel Prize.  
- **1910** – **[Harry Fielding Reid](/Harry_Fielding_Reid)]** proposed the **[elastic rebound theory](/Elastic-rebound_theory)** for earthquake generation.  
- **1910** – **[Lord Rayleigh]** introduced **[Rayleigh flow]**, describing flow with heat addition or removal.  
- **1911** – **[Augustus Edward Hough Love](/Augustus_Edward_Hough_Love)]** predicted **[Love surface waves](/Love_wave)**, a type of seismic vibration confined to the Earth’s surface.  
- **1915–1916** – **[Frederick W. Lanchester](/Frederick_W._Lanchester)** formulated **[Lanchester's laws](/Lanchester%27s_laws)**, early quantitative models for aerodynamic drag and lift.  
- **1915–1917** – **[George Barker Jeffery](/George_Barker_Jeffery)]** and **[Georg Hamel](/Georg_Hamel)]** described **[Jeffery–Hamel flow](/Jeffery%E2%80%93Hamel_flow)**, a class of steady motions in cylindrical containers.  
- **1916** – **[Horace Lamb](/Horace_Lamb)]** coined the term **[vorticity](/Vorticity)**, a fundamental quantity in fluid dynamics.  
- **1916** – **[Eugene C. Bingham](/Eugene_C._Bingham)]** studied **[Bingham plastics](/Bingham_plastic)**, a class of yield‑stress fluids.  
- **1916–1923** – Research by **[Lord Rayleigh]** and later **[G. I. Taylor](/G._I._Taylor)** elucidated the **[Rayleigh–Taylor instability](/Rayleigh%E2%80%93Taylor_instability)**, governing the growth of interfacial disturbances under acceleration.  
- **1917** – **[Lamb]** introduced **[Lamb waves](/Lamb_waves)**, elastic waves propagating in thin plates.  
- **1918** – **[Ludwig Prandtl](/Ludwig_Prandtl)]** developed a practical theory for flow over wings, laying the foundation for modern aerodynamics.  
- **1919** – **[Jacob Bjerknes](/Jacob_Bjerknes)]** formulated the **[Norwegian cyclone model](/Norwegian_cyclone_model)**, explaining mid‑latitude atmospheric circulation.  
- **1920** – **[Nikola Tesla](/Nikola_Tesla)]** patented the **[Tesla valve](/Tesla_valve)**, a one‑way valve relying on flow resistance, expanding the field of **[fluidics](/Fluidics)**.  
- **1920** – **[Bingham]** coined the term **[rheology](/Rheology)**, the science of flow and deformation of matter.  
- **1921** – **[Theodore von Kármán](/Theodore_von_K%C3%A1rm%C3%A1n)]** described **[Von Kármán swirling flow](/Von_K%C3%A1rm%C3%A1n_swirling_flow)** and the eponymous **[Kármán vortex street](/K%C3%A1rm%C3%A1n_vortex_street)**, critical for understanding drag and vibration.  
- **1921** – **[Alan Arnold Griffith](/Alan_Arnold_Griffith)]** proposed a theory of **[fracture mechanics](/Fracture_mechanics)**, linking crack tip stress to material failure.  
- **1922** – The first **[supersonic wind tunnel](/Supersonic_wind_tunnel)** was constructed at the **[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)](/National_Physical_Laboratory_(United_Kingdom))**, enabling controlled supersonic testing.  
- **1926** – **[Einstein]** solved the **[tea leaf paradox](/Tea_leaf_paradox)**, explaining upward migration of particles in a rotating fluid.  
- **1925** – **[Jakob Ackeret](/Jakob_Ackeret)]** published foundational theories of supersonic airfoil design.  
- **1926** – **[Erwin Madelung](/Erwin_Madelung)]** linked quantum mechanics to fluid dynamics via the **[quantum hydrodynamics](/Quantum_hydrodynamics)]** equations, known as the **[Madelung equations](/Madelung_equations)**.  
- **1931** – **[Sylvia Skan](/Sylvia_Skan)]** and **[Victor Montague Falkner](/Victor_Montague_Falkner)]** derived the **[Falkner–Skan boundary layer](/Falkner%E2%80%93Skan_boundary_layer)** equations, describing similarity solutions for external flows.  
- **1932** – **[Igor Tamm](/Igor_Tamm)]** introduced the concept of the **[phonon](/Phonon)** as the quantum of lattice vibrations, connecting elasticity to quantized excitations.  
- **1937** – **[Pyotr Kapitsa](/Pyotr_Kapitsa)]** discovered **[superfluidity](/Superfluidity)]** in **[helium‑4](/Helium-4)**, a frictionless phase of matter. Independently, **[John F. Allen](/John_F._Allen_(physicist))** and **[Don Misener](/Don_Misener)]** reported the same phenomenon.&#91;61&#93; &#91;62&#93;  
- **1938** – **[Philip Saffman](/Philip_Saffman)]** and **[G. I. Taylor]** described the **[Saffman–Taylor instability](/Saffman%E2%80%93Taylor_instability)**, observed when a less viscous fluid displaces a more viscous one in a porous medium.  
- **1937** – **[Lev Landau](/Lev_Landau)]** introduced **[Landau theory](/Landau_theory)** of phase transitions, providing a macroscopic description of critical phenomena.  
- **1940–1941** – **[László Tisza](/L%C3%A1szl%C3%B3_Tisza)]** and **[Landau]** proposed the **[two‑fluid model](/Two-fluid_model)** for helium, describing it as a mixture of normal and superfluid components.  
- **1941** – **[Landau]** identified **[second sound](/Second_sound)**, a thermal wave propagating in superfluids.  
- **1942** – **[Hannes Alfvén](/Hannes_Alfvén)]** formulated the basics of **[magnetohydrodynamics](/Magnetohydrodynamics)]**, introducing **[Alfvén waves](/Alfvén_wave)** in magnetized plasmas.&#91;65&#93; &#91;66&#93;  
- **1948** – **[Milton S. Plesset](/Milton_S._Plesset)]** refined the **[Rayleigh–Plesset equation](/Rayleigh%E2%80%93Plesset_equation)** to include surface tension effects in bubble dynamics.  
- **1941** – **[Andrey Kolmogorov](/Andrey_Kolmogorov)]** unveiled a rigorous statistical theory of **[turbulence](/Turbulence)],** describing the cascade of kinetic energy across scales.  
- **1947–** – **[Karl Weissenberg](/Karl_Weissenberg)]** described the **[Weissenberg effect](/Weissenberg_effect)** in viscoelastic fluids under shear.  
- **1950** – **[James G. Oldroyd](/James_G._Oldroyd)]** introduced the **[Oldroyd‑B model](/Oldroyd-B_model)**, a constitutive equation for viscoelastic fluids.&#91;68&#93;  
- **1944** – **[Lewis Ferry Moody](/Lewis_Ferry_Moody)]** plotted the **[Darcy–Weisbach friction factor](/Darcy%E2%80%93Weisbach_equation)** against **[Reynolds number](/Reynolds_number)** for various roughness values, creating the now‑standard **[Moody chart](/Moody_chart)**.  
- **1961** – **[Eugene P. Gross](/Eugene_P._Gross)]** and **[Lev Pitaevskii](/Lev_Pitaevskii)]** formulated the **[Gross–Pitaevskii equation](/Gross%E2%80%93Pitaevskii_equation)],** governing the behavior of weakly interacting bosons in a condensate.&#91;69&#93; &#91;70&#93;  
- **1963** – **[Alex Kaye](/Alex_Kaye)]** described the **[Kaye effect](/Kaye_effect)** in viscoelastic liquids, where a moving contact line deposits a thin film.  
- **1972** – **[David Lee](/David_Lee_(physicist))**, **[Douglas Osheroff]**, and **[Robert Coleman Richardson](/Robert_Coleman_Richardson)]** discovered two distinct superfluid phases in **[helium‑3](/Helium-3)],** expanding the understanding of quantum fluids.  
- **1990** – The first **[micro total analysis system](/Total_analysis_system) (μTAS)** was demonstrated by **[Andreas Manz](/Andreas_Manz)]**, inaugurating the field of **[microfluidics](/Microfluidics)**.&#91;71&#93;  
- **1995** – The inaugural **[Bose–Einstein condensate](/Bose%E2%80%93Einstein_condensate)** was realized by **[Eric Cornell](/Eric_Allin_Cornell)]** and **[Carl Wieman](/Carl_Wieman)]** at the **[University of Colorado at Boulder](/University_of_Colorado_at_Boulder)]**, later confirmed by **[Wolfgang Ketterle](/Wolfgang_Ketterle)]** at MIT.  

---  

## 21st Century  

Recent advances continue to push the boundaries of fluid and continuum mechanics, especially at micro‑ and nano‑scales.  

- **c. 2000** – Development of **[droplet‑based microfluidics](/Droplet-based_microfluidics)]**, enabling high‑throughput single‑cell analysis and lab‑on‑a‑chip applications.&#91;73&#93; &#91;74&#93;  
- **2003** – **[Deborah S. Jin](/Deborah_S._Jin)]** and collaborators produced the first **[fermionic condensate](/Fermionic_condensate)],** a paired‑fermion analog of the Bose–Einstein condensate.&#91;75&#93;  

